review_blob: This is a once-in-a-while treat that has a great amount of flavor. Pair with burgers, fish and chips or brunch.

beer_brewer_name: Magic Hat Brewing Company (North American Breweries)
review_blob: Unique sour (pleasant) taste with delicate hops and malty finish. Nice balance with no off-flavors. Great with fish or chicken.
This a truly delicious brew with distinct flavors and aromas.  Drinkable, refreshing, but also elegant and unique.
Pours a beautiful, thick amber.  Slight citrus and strong hops on the nose.  Excellent beer in a can.  Highly Recommended
This seems okay with a pretty flavorful initial taste.  Enjoy the sweetness, but I wish there was more bite.

This is a terrific ale. I hope that they make it a permanent addition.  Dry hopped to perfection.  Refreshing ale.Earlier Rating: 8/2/2006 Total Score: 3Thick head, nice lacing, but way too hoppy.  Nice malt taste.  One of the best organic beers in the area.  Definitely worth a try, but it leans to a home-brew like quality.
Fun pils.  Golden with some nice fruity spice.  Refreshing and great with food.
Easily the biggest hops ever.  Very interesting.  Bought at Whole Foods ... kinda pricey, but a lot of fun.
Wortth a try, a bit sweet with unfamiliar aromas of mash and grass, not exactly pleasant. Drinkable but not really worth the $7.99 price. Brewed in CA with a Hawaiian brand.
A solid pilsner with a great balance of tart, sweet and body.  Pours a light amber.  Easy to drink and great with all beer food.
A solid pilsen, but nothing spectacular.  I love the brown bottle (keep it fresh) and the born on date.  Bought at TJs for $6.99/sixer.  85%
Got this from Safeway on sale.  Perfect malt, hop and spice balance.  Highly, highly recommended.  Almost as good as my favorite Stella Artois.  $6.99 a six pack.  200%.
Pours a dark golden yellow.  Nice hoppiness, and nice malt aftertaste.  Great for the price at TJs.  A great crisp fall beer.
Nice fresh aroma.  Citrus, hops and malts.  Very clear flavor with no real heavy bitterness. Lighter than other imports.
UPDATED: JUN 12, 2008
Pours a dark golden yellow with light head.  Nice spicy aroma with citrus and hoppy bite.  Recommended for a nice change of pace.  95%.  $7.49/sixer.
Pours a golden yellow with nice white foam.  Nice sweet malt and bite-y hops.  Nice balance.  A bit pricey. 95%. $8.99 a sixer at a local beershop.

Interesting strength in taste for a pils.  Pours a cloudy orange, yellow with thinning head.  Citrusy and bright with a nice pucker.  Interesting flavors with bold carbonation.  Good specialty beer.  $2.79 for 1/2 liter.  90%.

Pours a bubbly, cloudy yellow.  Great fruity, hoppy aroma.  Delicious, flavorful and complex.  Dry with not a lot of malty sweetness.  A great fine-drinking beer for special occasions.  Highly recommended.  Great with heavy food.  $2.99 for a 1/2 liter bottle.  120%

Pours a golden yellow.  Nice citrus with hoppy first taste.  Very good pils with a solid refreshing kick.  The aroma doesnt come through much, but the tastes are a nice change of pace.  For the price, $3 for a 16 oz bottle, it is worth a try, but not an everyday option.  90%.

Pours a dark golden with lots of bubbles.  Good smelling with nice malts.  First taste is bright with strong hop flavors.  Nice pils.  Probably would be better if it were fresher. There was dust on the bottles at  the local TJs. The flavor goes a little bitter after a while, but still good.   A good deal at $4.99 / sixer.  110%

Pours a nice golden yellow with white head.  The can suggests a certain temperature of about 40degrees F.  Nice flavor of hops and malts.   Nicely recommended for lager drinkers.  Smooth aftertaste... refreshing.  Only 4.99/sixer for US Pint size cans.  Easily a 200% value/flavor rating.
Pours a nice light golden head. Nice hops with light malt flavors.  A bit pricey for the effort.  $6.99 for a sixer at TJs.  80% rating

Opened bottle to a very promising aroma: citrus, hops and honey.  Pours a golden, foamy (thick) head.  Nice malty flavors with medium hoppy kick.  Very nice, although a bit expensive.  Lots of nice complexities so it is worth it.  $7.99 a six pack.  105%.

Pours a honey amber with small head. Strong toasted malts and bite of brandy-like hops.  Heavy with little or no carbonation.  Refreshing and complex, but not a lager in the traditional sense.  The trademarks of a lager (bright, bubbly and pale) are notably absent. Very tasty for Trader Joes at 5.99 a sixer. 110%

Pours golden with fluffy head and good carbonation.  Pretty light with a nice hoppy aftertaste.  This balances well with yeasty, spicy malt flavors.  There is a nice (in this brew at least!) brandy tone to this beer, similar to what you find in other western europe beers. This pils does well in a brown bottle.  Good light drink at the $10/ twelve pack price at TJs.  Recommended.

This is a pretty solid value beer.  I dont know where people get off complaining.  For the price, it is comparable (if not better) than other Mexi-lagers.  Far less sweet than the malty Tecate.  Recommended for the $4.99 sixer price or the $1.49/ 24 oz can.  100%.
Of the big three, I think this is the crispest most refreshing pale lager.  No icky sweet malts or rice-like graininess.  For the price $2.99/sixer, it is well worth the price.  105% value.

I am going to buy this again, because it is cheap, local and refreshing, but my score is lower than I expected.  It pours great with a nice white head and nice bubbles.  But the flavor is a little one dimensional.  I was hoping for a little spice, like you get from the malts from the TJs Bohemian (seemingly discontinued).  But this is a good start ... Id like to see some citrus and malt flavors to round out the flavors.  A solid 180% for the $4.99/sixer price.  Give it a try.

Nice solid frothy head.  Pale gold with good carbonation.  Sweet, but nicely balanced with a hoppy bitterness.  This is a solid lager, but I wish it had a date on the bottle.  These kinds of beers are hard to find, but they also tend to sit on shelves.  Its hard to figure out why they are on sale.   Not my favorite, but enjoyable for the $7.99/sixer price.  100%.
Okay, but no real flavor.  Pretty watery even for a lager.  Light citrus, malts and very light hops.  Nice carbonation. Very good for the $3.99/ six pack.

Pours a light golden, bubbly head.  Delicious.  Nice crisp lager with very little off flavors.  Nice hoppiness and very refreshing.  Recommended for the price ($9.99/twelve pack).  A great mid range beer.  150%

Pours a nice golden yellow.  Thin head but with good carbonation.  Aroma of corn, seawater (not a great sign).  A nice hoppy taste but goes away and you are left with a pretty grassy, sweet lager.  Not bad, but I was hoping for something more.

Pours a golden yellow (not pale).  Nice fruity sweet aroma of apricot and malt.  Very nice pilsener, not very flavorful, but that can be allowed given its enormous drinkability.  Great deal at $6.49/sixer at the local Longs Drugstore.  WIsh they had a brew date, but seems very fresh.  Recommended.  WIll drink again, again.
Pours pale yellow.  Way too sweet.  No flavor.  Kinda beer that needs lime.  Decent carbonation.  Needs to be cold.

Pours a light brown (like watered down cola).  Nice toasted malt, hoppy aroma.  Crisp with bread and chocolate background flavors.  Nice malts but not really bitter from all the hops and toasted (burnt malts).  A nice solid dunkel / bock for the $5.99/sixer at TJs.  Recommended.

This is a nice, fresh pale ale.  Very solid flavors and no ruddiness that you find with other organic brews.  Very comparable, if not better than, Sierra Nevada.  Highly recommended.  Brew date on bottle!  I picked it up for $7.49/a sixer at the local green store.  Check it out.
UPDATED: FEB 17, 2007

Aroma of very toasted malts and coffee and some spice (almost pepper). Pours a cola/coffee brown with thin tan head.  Very drinkable and great flavors of molasses and sweet coffee.  Not really chocolatey, but there is a lot of richness.  Nice bitter finish.
Very strong malt, grass aroma.  Bitter with a strong harsh finish.  I like it a lot, but brandy aftertaste is not what I expected.  The malts dont seem to be toasted much?
Pours a golden yellow with thin head.  Nice hop/malt aroma.  Nice bite with spice and orange flavors.  Good carbonation and excellent mouthfeel.  Recommended for its price.

Pours a pale yellow with a small, tight head. Aroma of hops and malts (nice!).  Flavors of spice and citrus.  Light with a nice kick at the end.  Nice pils!  Recommended for the price at TJs $6.49 a sixer.

Poured a pale yellow with good carbonation and lacing.  Nice hoppy, spicy aroma with a little citrus.  Pretty skunky, but not skunked because of the green bottle.  There is a creaminess to it.  Very acidic. Pretty refreshing.  Recommended for pils/lager drinkers.  I dont know if I like the sourness much.

This is a nicely balanced pale ale.  Pours a golden honey amber.  Good nose with malts and hops.  Not very bitter, because the malts are more upfront than other Pale Ales.    Nice spice and fruit flavors.  A bit pricey for the $7.99/ sixer, but worth a try.  A very solid organic brew from A-B.  The haters hate it, but, of course, they are blinded.
beer_name: Green Valley Brewing Stone Mill Pale Ale

review_blob: This is a strong, solid, and flavorful IPA.  I really appreciated the nose and aroma that held a tremendous about of heat and malt.  Highly recommended for the price $6.49/ sixpack
This is a fine red ale.  Pours a nice copper, amber with a nice head and fine lacing.  Nice  balance of malts and hops with a strong bitter kick.  Recommended.
beer_name: Moylans Dannys Irish Style Red Ale

review_blob: Pours a deep yellow with a small head.  Tastes very lagerish, with more malt than hop flavors.  Not bad, but not really a pale ale.  More pils than anything.  I cant really recommend it for the price of a $2.89/bomber.
Old anguish.  This could be better in a can.  No effort on the part of the brewers.  What do they do at brewer conventions?  Do they have to admit they brew this junk?

Pours a dark black/brown with brown/tan head.  Initial flavors of brandy, malts, chocolate, coffee and coal.  Not bad, but very intense for an oatmeal stout.   Not very creamy or fruity like other "sweet" stouts.  Recommended with reservations.
Nice copper head.  Warm ale with great body.  Citrus flavors.  Hoppy.  Recommended with reservations when it is very expensive.  No expiration date.
